# Nexus infra-service registry — declarative input to
# `monitor/bootstrap-recover.sh`.
#
# Copy this file to `monitor/services.registry` (operator-local,
# gitignored) and list the long-running infra services your deployment
# expects to be up. On a restart the orchestrator runs
# `bootstrap-recover.sh`, which relaunches each registered service that
# is BOTH unhealthy AND has no tmux window. Adding a new service is a
# one-line edit here — no code change.
#
# FORMAT — one service per line, FOUR required fields plus an OPTIONAL
# fifth and sixth, separated by single TABs (not spaces):
#
#     <name>\t<workdir>\t<launch-cmd>\t<healthcheck-cmd>[\t<logfile>[\t<policy>]]
#
#   name        tmux window name to host the service (also the
#               idempotency key — a window by this name means "already
#               running, do not relaunch").
#   workdir     directory the launch + healthcheck run in. `~` and
#               `$NEXUS_ROOT` are expanded. A missing workdir means the
#               service is skipped (its project isn't checked out here).
#   launch-cmd  shell command sent to the new tmux window. Prefer a
#               supervised restart-loop wrapper (it survives crashes
#               within the session; this registry survives the session
#               itself dying).
#   healthcheck shell command run in <workdir>; exit 0 == healthy.
#               Keep it cheap and fast (short curl timeout / pgrep /
#               test -f) — it runs on every recovery sweep.
#   logfile     OPTIONAL. The service's logfile. It serves two readers:
#               (1) the cockpit `monitor/svc.sh` tails it (dashboard
#               picks and the `logs <name>` verb), and
#               (2) `bootstrap-recover.sh` appends a HEADLESS launch's
#               stdout/stderr here when it (re)starts the service. `~`
#               and `$NEXUS_ROOT` are expanded; a relative path resolves
#               under <workdir>. Omit it and both fall back to
#               <workdir>/serve.log.
#   policy      OPTIONAL. The watcher's continuous service-health task
#               (monitor/watcher/_service_health.sh) reads this to decide
#               WHAT it does when the healthcheck fails past the self-heal
#               grace window. Two values:
#                 auto-restart  (default) grace → minimal-downtime restart
#                               (flap-controlled) → emit. Use for services
#                               where a blind restart is safe.
#                 emit-only     never auto-restart; after grace the watcher
#                               escalates to the orchestrator and lets it
#                               decide. Use where a blind restart is unsafe
#                               or wants human judgment (e.g. a service
#                               with side effects on relaunch, or one whose
#                               failure usually signals a deeper problem).
#               Omit it to inherit monitor.service_health.default_policy
#               (auto-restart). REQUIRES the 5th <logfile> field present
#               (give an explicit logfile, or leave it empty between two
#               TABs) — it is the 6th positional column.
#               NOTE: only the service-health task consumes this; bootstrap-
#               recover / svc.sh / version-restart ignore it (they read it
#               into a throwaway var so it can't corrupt their logfile).
#
# Lines beginning with `#` and blank lines are ignored. A line with
# fewer than the four required TAB fields is skipped with a warning,
# never fatal. 4-field rows remain valid — the 5th + 6th fields are additive.
#
# Validate your edits without launching anything:
#     monitor/bootstrap-recover.sh --list      # echo parsed records
#     monitor/bootstrap-recover.sh --dry-run    # decide + log, no launch
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# EXAMPLE ENTRIES (an example operator stack). Uncomment +
# adjust paths in your real `monitor/services.registry`. The columns
# below are TAB-separated; if you copy them, make sure your editor
# keeps the tabs. The trailing 5th column is the optional <logfile>; the
# 6th is the optional <policy> (auto-restart | emit-only).
#
# dolimap-serve   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj/website   ./serve-supervised.sh   curl -fsS -o /dev/null --max-time 3 http://localhost:8765/   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj/website/serve.log
#
# Same service, but pinned emit-only (watcher emits + lets the orchestrator
# decide instead of auto-restarting — the 6th column):
# dolimap-serve   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj/website   ./serve-supervised.sh   curl -fsS -o /dev/null --max-time 3 http://localhost:8765/   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj/website/serve.log   emit-only
#
# JupyterLab services (jupyter-*) are NOT hand-written here: run
# `monitor/jupyter-up.sh <project-dir>` and it appends/maintains the
# row itself (and `--down` removes it). A maintained row looks like:
# jupyter-myproj   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj   /abs/path/monitor/labsh-supervised.sh   /abs/path/monitor/jupyter-health.sh   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj/.jupyter/labsh-service.log
# deploy-watch    $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj/website   ./deploy-watch.sh   pgrep -f deploy-watch.sh   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/myproj/website/deploy.log
# annzarro        $NEXUS_ROOT/work/annzarro   ./run-supervised.sh   curl -fsS -o /dev/null --max-time 3 http://localhost:8766/   $NEXUS_ROOT/work/annzarro/annzarro.log
#
# The confined remote SSH endpoint (agent-channel RFC Part A) is NOT
# hand-written either: run `monitor/remote-up.sh` and it appends/maintains
# the row itself (`--down` removes it). For this service, PRESENCE OF THE ROW
# IS THE ENABLE SIGNAL — there is no separate config flag (RFC §4.8). It is
# pinned `emit-only` (6th column) — a network listener is never
# blind-restarted; a wedged sshd escalates to the orchestrator via
# `--- service health ---`. With no row the launch wrapper exits without
# listening and the healthcheck treats not-running as healthy. A maintained
# row looks like (TAB-separated):
# nexus-remote-ssh   $NEXUS_ROOT   /abs/path/monitor/remote-sshd-supervised.sh   /abs/path/monitor/remote-ssh-health.sh   $NEXUS_ROOT/monitor/.state/remote-ssh.log   emit-only
